references: Integrating FL into iterative pruning, as visualized in Fig.Â 1b, lottery federated learning (LotteryFL) enables distributed discovery of winning tickets by iterating the following operations [6]: each user (i) prunes its local model (or subnetwork), (ii) re-trains the local model after the re-initialization, (iii) uploads the resultant local subnetwork to a server averaging the subnetworks, and finally (iv) downloads the averaged parameters replacing those of the local subnetwork. While effective under stable connectivity with unlimited bandwidth, the communication efficiency and personalization capability become questionable under intermittent wireless connectivity with limited bandwidth. To be precise, (iv) entails unicasting different subnetworks to multiple users, which is not scalable under limited bandwidth. What is more, once a userâ€™s subnetwork becomes less correlated with the othersâ€™ at a certain communication round, the user can no longer contribute to other subnetworks nor be influenced by them. In other words, LotteryFL only cares about fast learners with high temporary task correlations, and ignore straggling learners who may bloom later, failing to reach the full potential.

As shown in Table I, the evidence becomes stronger for the asynchronous setting (C<1ğ¶1C<1), as FedAvgâ€™s performance plummets, when either local data is insufficient or participation ratio is low. Roughly speaking, FedAvg starts performing once it has more than 3,00030003{,}000 samples used for a round (C=0.5,nk=50formulae-sequenceğ¶0.5subscriptğ‘›ğ‘˜50C=0.5,n_{k}=50), while the lottery based algorithms start performing with as little as 240240240 samples (C=0.1,nk=20formulae-sequenceğ¶0.1subscriptğ‘›ğ‘˜20C=0.1,n_{k}=20). The solid performance of the lottery based algorithms in highly asynchronous settings serves as an evidence that the users with easy tasks exert too much influence on the global aggregate at when the total data is insufficient. In addition, CELL outperforms LotteryFL with consistent margin. This performance gain is an evidence that CELLâ€™s achievement of fairness, i.e. subsequently giving harder tasks opportunities exert more influence, helps all users, including fast learners and stragglers, to learn better.

As shown in Fig. 2(b)-(d), CELL shows significant improvement in communication efficiency. Especially, CELLâ€™s uplink (UL) efficiency in Fig. 2(b) is promising for cellular communications based learning systems, given the highly unbalanced nature of uplink (UL) and downlink (DL) performance of commercial 5G [16], i.e. UL having much lower capacity. As shown in Table II under different settings, CELLâ€™s UL efficiency is resilient against diverse tasks, because it prunes usersâ€™ models in even the harshest environment, consisting of highly heterogeneous tasks w.r.t. their difficulties and the level of correlation between them.
In addition, CELLâ€™s broadcasting architecture allows its downlink payload to be independent from the number of participating users. This makes CELL scalable for systems with large number of users. These results are surprising, because higher level of model sparsity often degrades performance [11].
